{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}

In the [[United States]], '''salvage sales''' are [[timber]] sales from [[United States National Forest|national forest]]s primarily to remove dead, infested, damaged, or down trees and associated trees for stand improvement. They are controversial partly because there are no standards for the number or proportion of trees that must be dead, infested, damaged, or down and partly because the [[United States Forest Service|U.S. Forest Service]] may retain the revenues to prepare and administer future salvage sales.

